vie season has essentially ended, and it=E2=80=99s fair to say that Hollywo=
od=E2=80=99s theatrical recovery, which was supposed to start in 2025, may =
have begun two and a half months ago. Barring a breakout from the long-gest=
ating remake of The Crow this weekend, the domestic box office from May thr=
ough August was (thus far) $3.34 billion, down 12 percent from 2023=E2=80=
=99s $3.77 billion but three percent above 2022=E2=80=99s $3.23 billion.

And if you dig deeper, as I=E2=80=99ve noted, the data is slightly rosier. =
Once June began with Sony=E2=80=99s $400 million worldwide-grossing Bad Boy=
s sequel, the industry saw nearly three months of uninterrupted best-case-s=
cenario performances. Franchise flicks either performed as well as hoped (A=
 Quiet Place: Day One, Despicable Me
4, Alien: Romulus, Bad Boys: Ride or Die) or aggressively overperformed (In=
