I. Good Year, Bad Summer

Warner Bros. had a killer run, especially overseas, from Barbie in July 202=
3 to Godzilla x Kong: The New Empire in April 2024. And it still has a lot =
to look forward to with Beetlejuice, Beetlejuice and Joker: Folie =C3=A0 De=
ux this fall. But the studio has had an abysmal summer, with dashed expecta=
tions all around=E2=80=94creating yet another headache for Warner Discovery=
 C.E.O. David Zaslav. The highly publicized dual release of M. Night Shyama=
lan=E2=80=99s Trap and his daughter Ishana Night Shyamalan=E2=80=99s The Wa=
tchers didn=E2=80=99t move the needle. Trap will earn around $75 million gl=
obally on an estimated $30 million budget=E2=80=94not terrible, but a far c=
ry from the director=E2=80=99s Split in 2016, which made $278 million globa=
lly on just a $9 million budget.

Then there=E2=80=99s
the $100 million+ first installment of Kevin Costner=E2=80=99s four-film Ho=
rizon: An American Saga, which outright bombed ($34 million worldwide) and =
was quickly sent to PVOD after it opened theatrically in June. Alas, it may=
