_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

II. 2010s Nostalgia Rules

The three biggest hits of the summer=E2=80=94Inside Out 2 ($1.6 billion wor=
ldwide thus far), Deadpool & Wolverine ($1.1 billion and counting), and Des=
picable Me 4 ($850 million and counting)=E2=80=94were continuations of I.P.=
 that was brand new to moviegoers during the previous decade. The kids who =
grew up on Minions, peak-era Pixar, and the first Deadpool (R-rated but com=
paratively kid-friendly) were eager to indulge in some generational nostalg=
ia.

Also riding the throwback train was the surprise success of the rerelease o=
f Laika=E2=80=99s 2009 hit Coraline, which =E2=80=9Copened=E2=80=9D with $2=
0 million worldwide. Likewise, Kingdom of the Planet of the Apes, which ear=
ned $400 million on a $160 million budget, was promoted as a continuation o=
f the popular 2011 to 2017 reboot/prequel trilogy, which earned $1.6 billio=
n,
rather than an entry into a franchise that began with the acclaimed 1968 fi=
lm starring Charlton Heston.

Alien: Romulus, however, did pitch itself as a sequel to the original 1979 =
Ridley Scott hit, skipping over Prometheus and Alien: Covenant. It was only=
 because of a surprisingly solid showing in China that Disney can boast of =
a $109 million global launch, rather than $75 million, for the $80 million =
Romulus. That has been an exception to the rule this decade, as the industr=
y now treats China=E2=80=99s box office as essentially found money. Speakin=
g of which...

III. Overseas Box Office Still Matters

The notion of a merely decently performing, or outright underperforming, do=
mestic earner being redeemed by overseas box office is less of a regular ev=
ent. Big films that scored high in North America used to do well internatio=
nally, often earning anywhere from 1.5x to 3x more overseas than domestical=
ly. However, that is no longer guaranteed, even for relatively successful d=
omestic releases.

You could argue that Inside Out 2, Deadpool & Wolverine, and Despicable Me =
4 earned so much in North American theaters that they don=E2=80=99t need to=
 earn a penny overseas for profitability. However, three key releases that =
earned decent to strong domestic numbers=E2=80=94The Fall Guy ($92 million)=
, IF ($111 million), and Twisters ($235 million thus far)=E2=80=94qualified=
 as global misses due to comparatively poor overseas earnings.
Indeed, Twisters may gross less overseas than Warners=E2=80=99 2014 found-f=
ootage tornado flick Into the Storm, which complicates the story that domes=
tic distributor Universal would like to tell about its $155 million disaste=
r sequel. If at all possible, perhaps the next batch of tentpoles should be=
 budgeted at a level where a 50-50 domestic/overseas split is enough to qua=
lify as profitable.

IV. The Barbie Comlex

It=E2=80=99s pretty terrible that Hollywood has to rely on a few $1.3 billi=
on- to $1.6 billion-grossing blockbusters to paper over an inconsistent sla=
te to get anywhere near 2010s-level box office totals. However, in the past=
 three years, we=E2=80=99ve seen seven such megahits in Spider-Man: No Way =
Home, Top Gun: Maverick, Avatar: The Way of Water, The Super Mario Bros. Mo=
vie, Barbie, Inside Out 2, and Deadpool & Wolverine. And we can all expect =
James Cameron=E2=80=99s third Avatar to provide another $2 billion blowout =
in late 2025. In fact, only two years between 2013 and 2019 didn=E2=80=99t =
have at least two $1.2 billion earners=E2=80=942014, which was topped by th=
e $1.1 billion-grossing Transformers: Age of Extinction, and 2016, which wa=
s topped by the $1.1 billion-grossing Captain America: Civil War.

But the consolidation of the moviegoing experience, where more of the annua=
l spend is devoted to a smaller number of releases, means that we=E2=80=99r=
e getting a semiregular output of these big-swinging, all-quadrant franchis=
e flicks. This means each year is likely to bring a couple of once-unthinka=
bly huge, industry-sized tent poles. And, more than ever, the studios need =
them to work.

