x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">It=E2=80=99s pretty=
 terrible that Hollywood has to rely on a few <i>$1.3 billion</i>-<i> to $1=
=2E6 billion</i>-grossing blockbusters=20=
to paper over an inconsistent slate to=
 get anywhere <i>near</i> 2010s-level box office totals. However, in the pa=
st three years, we=E2=80=99ve seen seven such megahits in <i>Spider-Man: No=
 Way Home, Top Gun: Maverick, Avatar: The Way of Water, The Super Mario Bro=
s. Movie, Barbie, Inside Out 2</i>, and <i>Deadpool &amp; Wolverine</i>. An=
d we can all expect <b>James Cameron</b>=E2=80=99s third <i>Avatar </i>to p=
rovide another $2 billion blowout in late 2025. In fact, only two years bet=
ween 2013 and 2019 <i>didn=E2=80=99t</i> have at least two $1.2 billion ear=
ners=E2=80=942014, which was topped by the $1.1 billion-grossing <i>Transfo=
rmers: Age of Extinction</i>, and 2016, which was topped by the $1.1 billio=
n-grossing <i>Captain America: Civil War</i>.
<br/><br/>But the consolidation of the moviegoing experience, where more of=
 the annual spend is devoted to a smaller number of releases, means that we=
=E2=80=99re getting a semiregular output of these big-swinging, all-quadran=
t franchise flicks. This means each year is likely to bring a couple of onc=
e-unthinkably huge, industry-sized tent poles. And, more than ever, the stu=
dios need them to work.<br/></td>
